= Chapter 6: The Shadowed Heart
\
The Warden’s massive stone chest heaved. The beautiful, clear teal glow of its Echo Crystal heart was gone, replaced by a dark, oily midnight-blue that seemed to swallow the light. The fine, fuzzy tendrils of the skulk were rapidly climbing up its arms, weaving through the cracks in its deepslate armor like living veins.

It raised its heavy head. Without eyes, it couldn't see Valen, but its long, rib-like stone antenna were twitching frantically, scanning the cold night air.

Valen took a sharp breath in terror. The sound of his gasp was tiny, but to the corrupted Warden, it was as loud as a thunderclap.

The machine let out a terrifying, distorted roar—a sound that combined a grinding stone engine with a ghostly scream. It raised its massive fists, ready to slam them down right where Valen was standing.

Instantly, Valen’s training kicked in. It tracks sound!

Before the fists could crush him, Valen threw himself backward, hitting the ground and rolling into the shadows of a stone archway. He forced himself to stay completely still. He held his breath, his heart drumming so loudly against his ribs he was afraid the monster would hear it.

The Warden’s fists slammed into the cobblestone, shattering the deepslate blocks into flying fragments. The machine paused, its antenna wiggling. It tilted its head, listening into the darkness. It was barely three blocks away from Valen. The ink-black skulk moss on its legs was pulsing in perfect time with its broken heart.

Valen slowly reached into his leather apron. His fingers brushed against a handful of loose redstone dust and a single, heavy iron bolt. He carefully gripped the bolt, took aim at the far side of the plaza, and tossed it.

CLINK.

The iron bolt bounced against a musical fountain across the square.

The Warden’s head snapped instantly toward the sound. With terrifying speed, the massive machine charged away from Valen, its heavy stone feet thudding against the ground as it rushed the fountain, smashing it into bits of marble and redstone wire.

Valen didn't waste a second. Keeping his knees bent and his footsteps completely silent—sneaking through the shadows just like he had seen the explorers do in dangerous caves—he scrambled away from the plaza and sprinted toward Master Elian’s tower.

"Master Elian! Wake up! You have to wake up!" Valen shouted, bursting through the heavy oak doors of the chief engineer's workshop.

Elian was asleep at his desk, his copper goggles pushed up onto his forehead. He blinked sleepily, rubbing his eyes. "Valen? What in the world is the matter? Is it time for the morning harvest already?"

"No! The skulk! It’s infecting the Wardens!" Valen cried out, leaning against the desk, chest heaving. "I saw it in the plaza. The dark moss... it climbed up the Warden’s legs and corrupted its crystal heart. It attacked me, Master! It smashed the fountain! It didn't recognize me at all!"

Elian frowned, standing up and smoothing his robes. "Valen, you’ve been working too hard. The Wardens are made of solid deepslate and iron. They cannot be 'infected' by moss. They are machines."

"But they run on sound energy!" Valen argued, desperation cracking his voice. "The skulk feeds on sound, too. They are connected, Master! The skulk is rewriting their programming!"

Before Elian could answer, a strange, low hum vibrated through the floorboards of the tower. It wasn't the happy, rhythmic thrum of the city's power grid. It was a chaotic, overlapping series of clicks and groans.

Elian walked over to his balcony and pushed open the stained-glass windows. Valen crowded in next to him, looking down at the city.

The sunless sky of Luminos-Vara was usually a beautiful sea of blue lanterns. But tonight, half of the lanterns were dark. And from the Central Plaza, a massive, dark shadow was growing.

The Grand Gateway was leaking.

The giant deepslate frame was completely covered in a thick, bubbling layer of midnight-blue skulk. It looked as if a dark, alien liquid was pouring out from the portal window, spilling over the plaza and stretching down the main streets like a web of black ice.

And marching out of the darkness of the portal were more Wardens. But they weren't the clean, pristine protectors built by the citizens. These Wardens were covered in skulk from head to toe. Their bone-stone rib cages were cracked open, and their hearts pulsed with a blinding, angry darkness.

Worse yet, the city's own guard Wardens, which had been standing watch around the plaza, were stumbling into the dark moss. One by one, their antenna twitched violently. One by one, their peaceful teal lights flickered and died, replaced by the corrupted midnight-blue.

"Great Inventors protect us," Elian whispered, his face turning pale as a sheet. "The machines... they're turning against the city."

Down below, an alarm bell began to ring out, its loud CLANG-CLANG-CLANG echoing through the caverns to wake the sleeping citizens.

"No! Tell them to stop the bell!" Valen screamed in horror.

But it was too late. The loud, ringing sound of the alarm bell rippled through the streets. In response, a dozen corrupted Wardens stopped in their tracks. Their antenna snapped upright, locking onto the sound of the bell—and the screams of the terrified citizens who were just waking up.